  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment.",
    "deviceClass": "Class III",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.",
    "modelInfluence": "High",
    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/vad-hemolysis-cfd-adequate",
      "type": "Claim",
      "name": "CFD model adequately predicts absolute hemolysis index for VAD conditions",
      "description": "The CFD hemolysis model, employing the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law damage accumulation integrated along Lagrangian particle trajectories, has been exercised across all five target flow-speed operating points for the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry. Mesh independence was demonstrated through a three-level refinement study (8 M, 18 M, and 34 M hexahedral cells) with normalised hemolysis index (nHI) variation below 3% between the two finest levels. Turbulence closure uses the SST k-omega model validated against PIV velocity field measurements from Stewart et al. (2012) showing mean velocity error below 8% across the impeller passage. Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification (N=2000 Latin-hypercube samples) propagated inlet boundary condition uncertainty, fluid viscosity variability (±5%), and power-law exponent uncertainty (α: 0.765±0.035, β: 0.062±0.008) yielding 95th-percentile nHI predictions remaining below the clinical threshold of 0.01 g/100 L at all operating points. Experimental hemolysis data from the FDA inter-laboratory study (Herbertson et al., 2015) were used as the reference benchmark; predicted nHI values fall within one experimental standard deviation for four of five operating points and within 1.5 standard deviations for the fifth. The totality of verification, validation, and uncertainty quantification activities supports the conclusion that the model is adequate for predicting absolute hemolysis levels under VAD operating conditions at the stated risk level."
    }
  ],
